### Decoded Contents

Referencing the [Appendix of RFC 8017](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8017#appendix-A.1.2), I expect that the modulus `n`, public exponent `e`, private exponent `d`, prime number `p`, and prime number `q` will be included in the private key file. The Appendix mentions some other information that will be present in the private key file, but the things I listed are the most relevant to us. 

I pasted the contents of my private key file into [Lapo Luchini's ASN.1 decoder](https://lapo.it/asn1js/) and pressed the `decode` button to decode the data.

I use the [Wikipedia page for the DER encoding format](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X.690) to interpret the following integers.

### The Modulus (n)

The first relevant integer is given by the following hexdump:

```
02 82 01 81 00 A0 FA E1 0C 98 1D 53 BE C4 57 D2 5C 36 05 FC B8 30 B1 68 E7 8A 3F AB 41 DC F8 2A CE 1B 0B 3B BC 8F C6 35 72 EE 0B AA B6 0A 00 45 02 1E BD 28 2E CE 1B D7 4A 71 4E 44 C4 BD 97 D4 79 F1 74 F8 9B DE 5F B5 45 93 F6 F2 E2 05 B2 01 A4 DB A8 76 33 D8 62 85 24 CD BD 5D D5 2C 98 E2 D1 20 9D 96 A2 4D 7A 91 7B A3 95 B1 69 0F 50 CF 46 F2 15 5E B7 1D 57 54 F6 57 D7 24 00 54 75 B4 E3 34 96 8F CC D9 C0 79 FB 1F 27 77 2C 6D 28 D1 0B 5B 43 92 A4 CA 08 24 37 FF D2 72 D3 9A C9 43 6B 9E A9 3D 26 00 A5 0C 9C C9 31 DE DF E4 46 10 83 30 A8 38 C9 F3 58 E3 0B 39 1D 6F A9 F6 48 A8 C9 A7 67 48 D9 88 47 D4 0E ED 0A 88 7D 4F EC 73 0A B0 77 E3 BC E9 95 45 C0 21 3C C4 0C 4A CD 9D F0 E6 F5 8E 88 65 9B D5 42 9C 04 E7 A6 80 7E 0E 31 DB 65 88 E1 F5 FA FE 37 3C 05 83 0A DB 3F 12 56 34 9B 94 17 33 0A 1A CB 2D 8B A1 9A 23 B6 82 1D 35 6B F2 EA B4 ED 88 AD C8 24 E4 92 F8 6D 1A F0 7E 7B D1 9A B2 0E 28 92 7A F2 09 9D B2 11 71 3A 22 C2 3C 6E F5 B9 D8 45 56 A4 79 15 D9 DF 00 75 D6 2F 19 16 9E 6B 0C B6 94 54 B6 8F DC 86 48 E8 58 E9 73 C3 A7 18 6F 1E 26 70 42 E2 12 26 04 7E BC 79 AF FD 0C 77 9D B2 34 DA BD B4 73 19 0E 0E 12 42 4E 89 39 C9 A6 22 A4 42 39 51 E7 A2 A7 85 7C 43 8B 6F
```

This represents `n`, the modulus.
* The first byte `0x02` means that the following data represents an integer. 
* The second byte `0x82` means that the integer is definite, long, and that the next 2 bytes contain the length of the integer. 
* The next two bytes `0x0181` contain the length of the integer. `0x0181` is 385 in decimal, so the integer is 385 bytes long.
* The remaining 385 bytes are the value of the integer `n`.
* Therefore, `n = `.

### The Public Exponent (e)

The second relevant integer is `0x0203010001`. This represents `e`, the public exponent. 
* The first byte `0x02` means that the following data represents an integer. 
* The second byte `0x03` means that the integer is definite, short, and 3 bytes long.
* The remaining three bytes are the value of the integer `e`: `0x010001` (`65537` in decimal).
* Therefore, `e = 0x010001 = 65537`.

### Decoded Contents

Referencing the [Appendix of RFC 3447](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3447#appendix-A.1.1), I expect that the modulus `n` and the public exponent `e` will be included in the public key file. 

I pasted the contents of my public key file into [Michael Holtstrom's ASN.1 decoder](http://ldh.org/asn1.html) and pressed the `convert` button to decode the data.

This ASN.1 decoder returned the following output:
```
U.P.SEQUENCE {
   U.P.INTEGER 
   U.P.INTEGER 0x010001 (65537 decimal)
}
```

* The first integer is the modulus `n`.
* Therefore, `n = `. 
* The second integer is the public exponent `e`. 
* Therefore, `e = 0x010001 = 65537`.
